SH.CON.1524.FE.ZS-diseasePrevention.def: Condom use, female is the percentage of the female population ages 15-24 who used a condom at last intercourse in the last 12 months.
SH.CON.1524.FE.ZS-diseasePrevention.name: Condom use, population ages 15-24
SH.CON.1524.FE.ZS-diseasePrevention.source: Demographic and Health Surveys, and UNAIDS.

SH.CON.1524.MA.ZS-diseasePrevention.def: Condom use, male is the percentage of the male population ages 15-24 who used a condom at last intercourse in the last 12 months.
SH.CON.1524.MA.ZS-diseasePrevention.name: Condom use, population ages 15-24
SH.CON.1524.MA.ZS-diseasePrevention.source: Demographic and Health Surveys, and UNAIDS.

SH.H2O.BASW.RU.ZS-diseasePrevention.def: The percentage of people using at least basic water services.  This indicator encompasses both people using basic water services as well as those using safely managed water services.  Basic drinking water services is defined as drinking water from an improved source, provided collection time is not more than 30 minutes for a round trip.  Improved water sources include piped water, boreholes or tubewells, protected dug wells, protected springs, and packaged or delivered water.
SH.H2O.BASW.RU.ZS-diseasePrevention.name: People using at least basic drinking water services
SH.H2O.BASW.RU.ZS-diseasePrevention.source: WHO/UNICEF Joint Monitoring Programme (JMP) for Water Supply, Sanitation and Hygiene (washdata.org).

SH.H2O.SMDW.RU.ZS-diseasePrevention.name: People using safely managed drinking water services
SH.H2O.SMDW.RU.ZS-diseasePrevention.source: WHO/UNICEF Joint Monitoring Programme (JMP) for Water Supply, Sanitation and Hygiene (washdata.org).

SH.IMM.HEPB-diseasePrevention.def: Child immunization rate, hepatitis B is the percentage of children ages 12-23 months who received hepatitis B vaccinations before 12 months or at any time before the survey. A child is considered adequately immunized after three doses.
SH.IMM.HEPB-diseasePrevention.name: Immunization

SH.IMM.IDPT-diseasePrevention.def: Child immunization, DPT, measures the percentage of children ages 12-23 months who received DPT vaccinations before 12 months or at any time before the survey. A child is considered adequately immunized against diphtheria, pertussis (or whooping cough), and tetanus (DPT) after receiving three doses of vaccine.
SH.IMM.IDPT-diseasePrevention.name: Immunization

SH.IMM.MEAS-diseasePrevention.def: Child immunization, measles, measures the percentage of children ages 12-23 months who received the measles vaccination before 12 months or at any time before the survey. A child is considered adequately immunized against measles after receiving one dose of vaccine.
SH.IMM.MEAS-diseasePrevention.name: Immunization

SH.MLR.NETS.ZS-diseasePrevention.def: Use of insecticide-treated bed nets refers to the percentage of children under age five who slept under an insecticide-treated bednet to prevent malaria.
SH.MLR.NETS.ZS-diseasePrevention.name: Use of insecticide-treated bed nets
SH.MLR.NETS.ZS-diseasePrevention.source: UNICEF, State of the World's Children, Childinfo, and Demographic and Health Surveys.

SH.MLR.TRET.ZS-diseasePrevention.def: Malaria treatment refers to the percentage of children under age five who were ill with fever in the last two weeks and received any appropriate (locally defined) anti-malarial drugs.
SH.MLR.TRET.ZS-diseasePrevention.name: Children with fever receiving antimalarial drugs
SH.MLR.TRET.ZS-diseasePrevention.source: UNICEF, State of the World's Children, Childinfo, and Demographic and Health Surveys.
SH.MLR.TRET.ZS-diseasePrevention.units: % of children under age 5 with fever

SH.STA.ARIC.ZS-diseasePrevention.def: Children with acute respiratory infection (ARI) who are taken to a health provider refers to the percentage of children under age five with ARI in the last two weeks who were taken to an appropriate health provider, including hospital, health center, dispensary, village health worker, clinic, and private physician.
SH.STA.ARIC.ZS-diseasePrevention.name: ARI treatment
SH.STA.ARIC.ZS-diseasePrevention.source: UNICEF, State of the World's Children, Childinfo, and Demographic and Health Surveys.
SH.STA.ARIC.ZS-diseasePrevention.units: % of children under 5 taken to a health provider

SH.STA.BASS.RU.ZS-diseasePrevention.def: The percentage of people using at least basic sanitation services, that is, improved sanitation facilities that are not shared with other households.  This indicator encompasses both people using basic sanitation services as well as those using safely managed sanitation services.   Improved sanitation facilities include flush/pour flush to piped sewer systems, septic tanks or pit latrines; ventilated improved pit latrines, compositing toilets or pit latrines with slabs.
SH.STA.BASS.RU.ZS-diseasePrevention.name: People using at least basic sanitation services
SH.STA.BASS.RU.ZS-diseasePrevention.source: WHO/UNICEF Joint Monitoring Programme (JMP) for Water Supply, Sanitation and Hygiene (washdata.org).

SH.STA.HYGN.RU.ZS-diseasePrevention.def: The percentage of people living in households that have a handwashing facility with soap and water available on the premises. Handwashing facilities may be fixed or mobile and include a sink with tap water, buckets with taps, tippy-taps, and jugs or basins designated for handwashing. Soap includes bar soap, liquid soap, powder detergent, and soapy water but does not include ash, soil, sand or other handwashing agents.
SH.STA.HYGN.RU.ZS-diseasePrevention.name: People with basic handwashing facilities including soap and water
SH.STA.HYGN.RU.ZS-diseasePrevention.source: WHO/UNICEF Joint Monitoring Programme (JMP) for Water Supply, Sanitation and Hygiene (washdata.org).

SH.STA.HYGN.UR.ZS-diseasePrevention.source: WHO/UNICEF Joint Monitoring Programme (JMP) for Water Supply, Sanitation and Hygiene (washdata.org).

SH.STA.ORCF.ZS-diseasePrevention.def: Children with diarrhea who received oral rehydration and continued feeding refer to the percentage of children under age five with diarrhea in the two weeks prior to the survey who received either oral rehydration therapy or increased fluids, with continued feeding.
SH.STA.ORCF.ZS-diseasePrevention.name: Diarrhea treatment
SH.STA.ORCF.ZS-diseasePrevention.source: UNICEF, State of the World's Children, Childinfo, and Demographic and Health Surveys.
SH.STA.ORCF.ZS-diseasePrevention.dim: % of children under 5 receiving oral rehydration and continued feeding
SH.STA.ORCF.ZS-diseasePrevention.units: % of children under 5 receiving oral rehydration and continued feeding

SH.STA.ORTH-diseasePrevention.def: Percentage of children under age 5 with diarrhea in the two weeks preceding the survey who received oral rehydration salts (ORS packets or pre-packaged ORS fluids).
SH.STA.ORTH-diseasePrevention.name: Diarrhea treatment
SH.STA.ORTH-diseasePrevention.source: UNICEF, State of the World's Children, Childinfo, and Demographic and Health Surveys.
SH.STA.ORTH-diseasePrevention.dim: % of children under 5 who received ORS packet
SH.STA.ORTH-diseasePrevention.units: % of children under 5 who received ORS packet

SH.STA.SMSS.RU.ZS-diseasePrevention.def: The percentage of people using improved sanitation facilities that are not shared with other households and where excreta are safely disposed of in situ or transported and treated offsite. Improved sanitation facilities include flush/pour flush to piped sewer systems, septic tanks or pit latrines: ventilated improved pit latrines, compositing toilets or pit latrines with slabs.
SH.STA.SMSS.RU.ZS-diseasePrevention.name: People using safely managed sanitation services
SH.STA.SMSS.RU.ZS-diseasePrevention.source: WHO/UNICEF Joint Monitoring Programme (JMP) for Water Supply, Sanitation and Hygiene (washdata.org).

SH.TBS.CURE.ZS-diseasePrevention.def: Tuberculosis treatment success rate is the percentage of all new tuberculosis cases (or new and relapse cases for some countries) registered under a national tuberculosis control programme in a given year that successfully completed treatment, with or without bacteriological evidence of success ("cured" and "treatment completed" respectively).
SH.TBS.CURE.ZS-diseasePrevention.name: Tuberculosis treatment success rate
SH.TBS.CURE.ZS-diseasePrevention.source: World Health Organization, Global Tuberculosis Report.

SH.TBS.DTEC.ZS-diseasePrevention.def: Tuberculosis case detection rate (all forms) is the number of new and relapse tuberculosis cases notified to WHO in a given year, divided by WHO's estimate of the number of incident tuberculosis cases for the same year, expressed as a percentage. Estimates for all years are recalculated as new information becomes available and techniques are refined, so they may differ from those published previously.
SH.TBS.DTEC.ZS-diseasePrevention.name: Tuberculosis case detection rate
SH.TBS.DTEC.ZS-diseasePrevention.source: World Health Organization, Global Tuberculosis Report.
